  "opinion": "As a 65-year-old self-employed waitress in Los Angeles, I've seen a lot change over the years, including how we share information. I only use social media a few times a month, mostly to keep up with my two children and share photos from my hiking and cycling trips, so I'm not constantly bombarded like some folks. But when I do scroll through, I notice fake content popping up—things that just don't seem right, like exaggerated news stories or doctored images. My approach is pretty straightforward, shaped by my Christian values and a practical outlook from years of working with people. First, I always take a moment to think before believing or sharing anything. If a post seems too sensational or doesn't match what I know from my own experiences, I'll check it out by looking at reliable sources, like local news or trusted websites. I've learned that being open-minded, which comes naturally to me, doesn't mean being gullible; it means considering different views but sticking to the facts. Since I'm not very neurotic, I don't get overly stressed about this stuff—I just see it as part of modern life that needs careful handling. I also rely on my community, talking to friends or family if I'm unsure, rather than trusting everything online. In my job, I deal with all sorts of customers, so I've developed a good sense for when someone's not being truthful, and I apply that to social media too. Ultimately, I believe managing fake content is about using common sense, staying informed through trusted channels, and not letting it disrupt the real connections that matter, like spending time outdoors with my hobbies. It's a balance of being cautious without becoming cynical, and I think that's something we can all strive for.",
